-- 27_parallel_solving — threaded solving of a claim's independent slow
-- components, with ENUM-typed variables in each component (session S),
-- shown as a measurable wall-clock win.
--
-- Session E added per-thread Z3 contexts for slow components, but only
-- for components whose variables were primitive (Int/Bool/Seq/Set). A
-- component containing an enum- or user-record-typed variable silently
-- fell back to the sequential single-context path, because the variable
-- carried a Z3 DatatypeSort bound to the runtime's main context. Session
-- S closes that gap: the parallel path now REPLAYS the program's enum +
-- datatype definitions into each worker's private context (Z3 interns
-- datatypes by name + variant structure, so the replayed sort unifies
-- with the one `Ast::translate` recreates for the moved assertions), so
-- enum-typed components parallelize too. That matters because almost
-- every real workload — Mario, the self-hosted passes — has an enum or
-- record variable somewhere.
--
-- The workload: six DISJOINT 16-queens boards (q0..q5), each a Seq(Int)
-- of length 16 with the standard column + diagonal distinctness
-- constraints. Each board additionally carries an enum-typed variable
-- `h ∈ Half` (`Half = LeftHalf | RightHalf`) classifying which half its
-- first queen occupies — a complete dispatch, so `h` is fully determined
-- by the board and joins the board's component WITHOUT changing the
-- search. Its presence is the point: each component now holds an
-- enum-typed variable (an `EnumVar`), which is exactly what used to force
-- the whole claim onto the sequential path. No board shares a variable
-- with any other, so the runtime decomposes `psolve` into six independent
-- slow components and solves them on parallel threads.
--
-- Verify the decomposition + that the enum components go parallel:
--     EVIDENT_FUNCTIONIZE_STATS=1 EVIDENT_PLAN_TIMING=1 \
--       evident effect-run examples/test_27_parallel_solving.ev
--     → [fz/stats] psolve: components=7 compiled=1 slow_components=6 ...
--     → [plan] 6 slow part(s) for psolve (parallel=true)   ← was false
--       before session S, because of the enum-typed `h` variables.
--
-- A/B the speedup (--timing reports per-claim wall time; the value
-- cache is disabled so the solve actually re-runs):
--     # threaded (default)
--     EVIDENT_VALUE_CACHE=0 evident effect-run …test_27… --timing
--     # single-threaded baseline
--     EVIDENT_PARALLEL_SLOW=0 EVIDENT_VALUE_CACHE=0 evident effect-run …test_27… --timing
--
-- Measured (Apple M4, 10 cores / 4 performance; `EVIDENT_PARALLEL_SLOW`
-- toggles it):
--     threaded ~48 ms   vs   single-threaded ~268 ms   ≈ 5.5× faster.
-- Two effects compound here (confirm both with EVIDENT_PLAN_TIMING=1):
--   1. The six board solves overlap instead of running back-to-back.
--   2. Each worker context is a *fresh, minimal* one carrying only its
--      own board (its replayed enum + just that board's assertions), so
--      a board solves in ~12-18 ms there vs ~47 ms on the sequential
--      path's shared main context (which has all six boards' Int + enum
--      decls interned). So the per-board solve is itself faster in
--      isolation — which is why the ratio exceeds the 6-board / 4-P-core
--      ceiling. Z3 is single-threaded per context; this is per-thread
--      contexts plus smaller per-context state, not a parallelized single
--      solve. Queens solve time is erratic across instances, so the exact
--      ratio wobbles run-to-run; the ≥2× floor holds comfortably.
--
-- Difficulty knobs: raise the board size (the `16`s — bigger boards
-- cost more per solve; queens time is erratic across n, but the tens
-- of n in the teens land in the tens-of-ms range), or add/remove a
-- board (its `q`/`h` declaration + length + Queens + FirstHalf lines)
-- to change the component count.

import "stdlib/runtime.ev"

enum Half = LeftHalf | RightHalf

-- N-queens as a reusable constraint: n queens on an n×n board, one per
-- row, no two sharing a column or a diagonal. Generic over the Seq's
-- element type — the body is pure Int arithmetic on q[i].
claim Queens(q ∈ Seq, n ∈ Nat)
    ∀ i ∈ {0..n-1} : (0 ≤ q[i] ∧ q[i] < n)
    ∀ i ∈ {0..n-1} : ∀ j ∈ {0..n-1} : i < j ⇒
        (q[i] ≠ q[j] ∧ q[i] + i ≠ q[j] + j ∧ q[i] - i ≠ q[j] - j)

-- Classify a board by which half its first queen occupies: LeftHalf for
-- column·2 < n, RightHalf otherwise. A complete dispatch — q[0] lands in
-- exactly one half — so `half` is fully determined by the board. This
-- single enum-typed variable joins q's connected component (it
-- references q[0]) without adding any search freedom; its job is to put
-- an `EnumVar` into each board's component, which is exactly what used
-- to force the whole claim onto the sequential single-context path.
-- Session S's cross-context datatype replay is what lets the component
-- parallelize anyway.
claim FirstHalf(q ∈ Seq, half ∈ Half, n ∈ Nat)
    (q[0] * 2 < n) ⇒ half = LeftHalf
    (q[0] * 2 ≥ n) ⇒ half = RightHalf

fsm psolve
    q0 ∈ Seq(Int)
    q1 ∈ Seq(Int)
    q2 ∈ Seq(Int)
    q3 ∈ Seq(Int)
    q4 ∈ Seq(Int)
    q5 ∈ Seq(Int)
    h0 ∈ Half
    h1 ∈ Half
    h2 ∈ Half
    h3 ∈ Half
    h4 ∈ Half
    h5 ∈ Half
    #q0 = 16
    #q1 = 16
    #q2 = 16
    #q3 = 16
    #q4 = 16
    #q5 = 16
    Queens(q0, 16)
    Queens(q1, 16)
    Queens(q2, 16)
    Queens(q3, 16)
    Queens(q4, 16)
    Queens(q5, 16)
    FirstHalf(q0, h0, 16)
    FirstHalf(q1, h1, 16)
    FirstHalf(q2, h2, 16)
    FirstHalf(q3, h3, 16)
    FirstHalf(q4, h4, 16)
    FirstHalf(q5, h5, 16)

    -- Constant effect list: references no board variable, so it stays
    -- its own (JIT-compiled) component and never couples the boards
    -- into one Z3 solve. The decomposition — and the parallelism — hangs
    -- on the boards being independent; coupling effects to a q would
    -- merge that board's component with this one.
    effects = ⟨Println("solved 6 independent enum-tagged 16-queens boards in parallel"), Exit(0)⟩

-- ── Static correctness tests ─────────────────────────────────────────
-- The FSM only proves "some assignment exists"; these pin known
-- placements so the Queens constraint is checked against ground truth.

-- [1,3,0,2] is the canonical 4-queens solution (columns per row).
claim sat_four_queens_known
    q ∈ Seq(Int)
    #q = 4
    q = ⟨1, 3, 0, 2⟩
    Queens(q, 4)

-- A column-clash placement (two queens in column 0) must be rejected.
claim unsat_four_queens_column_clash
    q ∈ Seq(Int)
    #q = 4
    q = ⟨0, 3, 0, 2⟩
    Queens(q, 4)

-- 3-queens has no solution (nor does 2-queens): the constraint is
-- unsatisfiable for n=3 regardless of placement.
claim unsat_three_queens
    q ∈ Seq(Int)
    #q = 3
    Queens(q, 3)

-- FirstHalf classifies a board by its first queen. With the 4-queens
-- solution [1,3,0,2] and n=4 (half = column·2 < 4, i.e. column < 2),
-- q[0]=1 is in the left half → LeftHalf. Pinning the expected enum
-- checks the enum-typed dispatch end-to-end (the same `EnumVar` the FSM
-- solves across worker contexts).
claim sat_first_half_known
    q ∈ Seq(Int)
    half ∈ Half
    #q = 4
    q = ⟨1, 3, 0, 2⟩
    half = LeftHalf
    FirstHalf(q, half, 4)

-- A wrong tag (q[0]=1 is in the left half → LeftHalf, not RightHalf)
-- must be rejected — confirms the dispatch actually constrains `half`.
claim unsat_first_half_wrong
    q ∈ Seq(Int)
    half ∈ Half
    #q = 4
    q = ⟨1, 3, 0, 2⟩
    half = RightHalf
    FirstHalf(q, half, 4)
